# Feature-first architecture

**Goal:** keep **business rules, domain UI, and flows** inside `src/features/<name>/`, **`src/app` thin**, and **shared code** outside feature folders. Full contract: `specs/001-project-foundation/contracts/feature-module-layout.md`.

## Principles

- **One feature = one cohesive module** (overview, transactions, …); do not mix domains in the same folder.
- **Routes only in `src/app`** — Expo Router files do not live under `features/`.
- **No direct coupling between features** — do not import `src/features/<other>/...` from another feature; use `src/lib`, `src/services`, shared contracts, or integration mechanisms defined by the project.
- **Rich screens in the feature**; **minimal routes** in `src/app` (short composition + screen re-export).

## Example folder tree

```text
src/
├── app/                          # Expo Router: routes and layouts only
│   ├── _layout.tsx
│   ├── index.tsx                 # may re-export a feature screen
│   └── transactions/
│       └── index.tsx             # ~1 line: re-export feature screen (see Source file naming)
├── features/
│   └── transactions/
│       ├── screens/              # MUST: route targets (default export)
│       ├── components/           # feature-only UI (not generic)
│       ├── hooks/                # hooks whose semantics belong to this feature
│       ├── services.ts|services/  # side effects / IO for this feature
│       └── README.md             # optional: one-line purpose
├── components/                   # cross-cutting UI (ui/, layout/, feedback/)
├── lib/                          # utilities, providers, storage, shared schemas
├── services/                     # global integrations (when they exist)
├── stores/                       # global state (Zustand); slices per agreed domain
└── hooks/                        # reusable hooks with no single feature owner
```

## What belongs where

| Location | Contents |
|----------|----------|
| `src/app/**` | Routes, groups, layouts; delegate to `features/.../screens`. Avoid business logic. |
| `features/<x>/screens` | Screens used as route `export default` targets. |
| `features/<x>/components` | Feature-specific components (they do not replace `src/components/ui`). |
| `features/<x>/hooks` | `useX` hooks that only make sense inside this feature. |
| `features/<x>/services` | API calls, flow persistence, feature side effects. |
| `src/components` | Design system and pieces reused across features. |
| `src/lib` | Helpers, shared Zod schemas, clients, config with no single feature owner. |

## Source file naming (`src/`)

- Use **kebab-case** file stems: `example-given.tsx`, `app-text.tsx`, `overview-placeholder-screen.tsx`, `ui-preferences.store.ts`. Do **not** use PascalCase or camelCase filenames (`ExampleGiven.tsx`, `exampleGiven.tsx`).
- **`index.ts` / `index.tsx`** — allowed for route entries and barrels.
- **Colocated tests** — same stem + `.test`: `app-text.test.tsx`.
- **Expo Router / framework exceptions** — keep required names literally (`_layout.tsx`, `+not-found.tsx`, `[id].tsx`, etc.); only the *optional* parts you add should still prefer kebab-case when not constrained by the framework.
- **Exports vs filenames** — kebab-case on disk; exported React components remain **PascalCase** (and hooks **camelCase**) inside the file, per TypeScript / React conventions.
- **Legacy** — existing non-kebab files MAY stay until refactored; **new** files under `src/` MUST follow this section.

## Route → screen wiring (default pattern)

Keep each route file in `src/app` short (ideally ≤ ~15 lines): local providers if needed + default export of the screen.

```tsx
// src/app/transactions/index.tsx
export { default } from '@/features/transactions/screens/transactions-placeholder-screen';
```

## Best practices

- Name feature folders in **kebab-case** aligned with routes (`recurring-bills`); avoid camelCase for the feature root folder (file stems: see **Source file naming** above).
- Place **tests** next to code (`*.test.tsx` beside the component) or under `src/tests/` if the project standardizes that — stay consistent with existing layout.
- Before adding a file, ask: **“Does this belong to a product domain?”** → feature; **“Is it generic or design-system?”** → `components` / `lib`.
